denoland/deno#21446.body:
Version: Deno 1.38.0
Platform: Microsoft Windows NT 10.0.22621.0 x64

----

## Scenario

A parent program: 

```typescript
import process from 'node:process';
import {spawn} from 'node:child_process';

const timer = `Running program`;
console.time(timer);
process.on('exit', () => console.timeEnd(timer));

const procNode = spawn('node', ['test.js']);
setTimeout(() => procNode.unref(), 1000);
```

that spawns a Node.js sub process implemented by `test.js`: 

```javascript
import {writeFile} from 'node:fs/promises';
import {setTimeout} from 'node:timers/promises';

console.log('node running');
await setTimeout(2000);
await writeFile('from-node.txt', 'Hello from Node.js');
```

## Bug

We can see Deno fails making the sub process go through because the file `from-node.txt` is never created.

If you're wondering about the different logs and timings, as well as why I spawn a child Node.js process: it's an example I adapted from [this Node.js issue](https://github.com/nodejs/node/issues/51018)

They help inspecting the behavior. Thanks to that, I can see in [System Informer](https://systeminformer.sourceforge.io/) that the sub process ***is*** created, but that it gets terminated at the same time as the parent due to the `unref()` call in the middle.

This code works with Node.js v20.9.0.

## Expectations

As part of the Node.js compatibility work, this should eventually be fixed.

In the meantime, update the [compatibility list](https://docs.deno.com/runtime/manual/node/compatibility) page which tells only this: 

> The ipc and overlapped stdio options are missing. Passing file descriptors by an integer value is missing.

## Context

- [Node.js issue #51018](https://github.com/nodejs/node/issues/51018)
- there's no builtin Deno alternative to *not* wait for a subprocess: 
  - #5501
  - #18189

