denoland/deno#29756.body:
Version: Deno 2.3.6

Deno's implementation of Cipher in node:crypto doesn't appear to correctly pad input's whos length is a multiple of the block size. In my case, the plaintext is 128 bytes. After encrypting, the ciphertext  is still 128 bytes. Assuming PKCS#7 padding, I would expect 144 bytes.

The [spec](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc5652#section-6.3) states,
> The padding can be removed unambiguously since all input is padded, including input values that are already a multiple of the block size, and no padding string is a suffix of another. 

So if padding is used, there should always be padding bytes and in this case, a full block of padding should have been added to the input.

Here is short snippet to reproduces the issue,
```ts
import { Buffer}  from "node:buffer"
import crypto from "node:crypto"

const key = crypto.randomBytes(32);
const iv = crypto.randomBytes(16);
const plaintext = crypto.randomBytes(128); // If this is 127 bytes, the input is correctly padded to 128 bytes.

const cipher = crypto.createCipheriv('aes-256-cbc', key, iv);
cipher.setAutoPadding(true);

const ciphertext = Buffer.concat([cipher.update(plaintext), cipher.final()]);
assert(ciphertext.length > plaintext.length); // Fails
```
Equivalent code in Node v24 works as expected.

I had a look at the implementation and I think the issue is in [this](https://github.com/denoland/deno/blob/090df402908bfa46382c188f026c3984a81cceab/ext/node/polyfills/internal/crypto/cipher.ts#L204C1-L208C6) block at the top of `Cipheriv.final`. 

```ts
if (this.#cache.cache.byteLength == 0) {
  const maybeTag = op_node_cipheriv_take(this.#context);
  if (maybeTag) this.#authTag = Buffer.from(maybeTag);
  return encoding === "buffer" ? Buffer.from([]) : "";
}
```

If auto padding is enabled then it shouldn't return an empty array. Instead the cipher should encrypt a block of padding and return that.

