Version: Deno 2.6.8

I'm trying to use the following NPM package that provides Node.js bindings to the FFmpeg/ Libav libraries:
https://www.npmjs.com/package/node-av

The following snippet produces an erroneous "cannot assign to read-only property" error in Deno (but not in Node):

```
import * as av from 'npm:node-av@5.2.1';
const f = new av.FormatContext();
f.allocContext();
f.getNative().flags = av.AVFMT_FLAG_DISCARD_CORRUPT;
```

The property cannot possibly be read-only (it has an accessor descriptor with both a getter and a setter):

```
import * as av from 'npm:node-av@5.2.1';
let f = new av.FormatContext();
let n = f.getNative();
console.log(Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(Object.getPrototypeOf(n), 'flags'));
```

```
{                                                                                                                       

  get: [Function (anonymous)],                                                                                          

  set: [Function (anonymous)],                                                                                          

  enumerable: false,                                                                                                    

  configurable: false                                                                                                   

}                                                                                                                       
 ```

Calling the setter directly instead of going through the property works:

```
import * as av from 'npm:node-av@5.2.1';
let f = new av.FormatContext();
f.allocContext();
let n = f.getNative();
console.log(`Current flags: ${n.flags}.`);
let d = Object.getOwnPropertyDescriptor(Object.getPrototypeOf(n), 'flags');
d.set.call(n, av.AVFMT_FLAG_DISCARD_CORRUPT);
console.log(`New flags: ${n.flags}`);
```

```
Current flags: 2097152.                                                                                                 

New flags: 256
```

This seems like it should be impossible. The property has a setter; it should be writable. Calling the setter manually works, so whatever underlying data it manipulates isn't read-only either.

